# Kubernetes Deployment Guide

This document describes how to deploy HWOA-RL-XAI as a Kubernetes scheduler extender on a real cluster, reproducing the experiments in Section 5.3 and Section 6.2 of the paper.

---

## Architecture

```
kube-scheduler
     │  Pod scheduling request
     ▼
HWOA-RL-XAI Extender API (Flask, GPU affinity)
     │  queries LSTM-AE predictions + PPO policy
     ▼
Scored node rankings (within 100 ms timeout)
     │
     ▼
Redis Message Bus ◄─── LSTM-AE Sidecar (Prometheus metrics → forecasts + anomaly alerts)
                              │
                    SHAP Worker Pod (async, publishes every 60s)
                              │
                    Grafana Dashboard (operator monitoring)
```

---

## Cluster Requirements

The paper's real-cluster experiments used:

| Node Type | Count | Spec | Tier |
|-----------|-------|------|------|
| Edge nodes | 8 | 4 cores, 8 GB RAM, Intel Atom C3758 | Edge |
| Regional nodes | 14 | 16 cores, 64 GB RAM, Intel Xeon E5-2680v4 | Regional |
| Hyperscale nodes | 10 | 32 cores, 256 GB RAM, AMD EPYC 7543 | Hyperscale |

Minimum requirement for local testing: 3-node cluster, 1 GPU node.

Kubernetes version: **v1.28+**

---

## Pre-deployment

### 1. Build Container Images

```bash
# Scheduler extender API
docker build -t hwoa-rl-xai-extender:latest k8s/scheduler-extender/
docker push <your-registry>/hwoa-rl-xai-extender:latest

# LSTM-AE sidecar
docker build -t hwoa-rl-xai-lstm:latest k8s/lstm-sidecar/
docker push <your-registry>/hwoa-rl-xai-lstm:latest

# SHAP worker
docker build -t hwoa-rl-xai-shap:latest k8s/shap-worker/
docker push <your-registry>/hwoa-rl-xai-shap:latest
```

Update image references in `k8s/manifests/*.yaml`.

### 2. Upload Pre-trained Models

```bash
# Create ConfigMap with model paths or use a PersistentVolumeClaim
kubectl create configmap hwoa-models \
  --from-file=lstm_ae=pretrained/lstm_ae_google.pt \
  --from-file=ppo_500vm=pretrained/hwoa_rl_xai_500vm.pt
```

---

## Deployment

```bash
# 1. Create namespace
kubectl create namespace hwoa-rl-xai

# 2. Deploy Redis message bus
kubectl apply -f k8s/manifests/redis.yaml -n hwoa-rl-xai

# 3. Deploy LSTM-AE sidecar (connects to Prometheus)
kubectl apply -f k8s/manifests/lstm-ae-sidecar.yaml -n hwoa-rl-xai

# 4. Deploy SHAP worker
kubectl apply -f k8s/manifests/shap-worker.yaml -n hwoa-rl-xai

# 5. Deploy the scheduler extender API
kubectl apply -f k8s/manifests/scheduler-extender-deployment.yaml -n hwoa-rl-xai

# 6. Register the extender with kube-scheduler
kubectl apply -f k8s/manifests/scheduler-policy.yaml -n kube-system

# 7. Verify
kubectl get pods -n hwoa-rl-xai
kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep kube-scheduler
```

### Resource Requests (per component)

| Component | CPU Request | CPU Limit | Memory Request | Memory Limit |
|-----------|------------|-----------|----------------|--------------|
| Extender API | 200m | 1000m | 512Mi | 2Gi |
| LSTM-AE Sidecar | 500m | 2000m | 1Gi | 4Gi |
| SHAP Worker | 200m | 500m | 512Mi | 1Gi |
| Redis | 100m | 200m | 256Mi | 512Mi |
| **Total** | **~1 core** | **~3.7 cores** | **~2.3 GB** | **~7.5 GB** |

---

## Extender API

The Flask API (`k8s/scheduler-extender/app.py`) exposes:

| Endpoint | Method | Description |
|----------|--------|-------------|
| `/filter` | POST | Filter infeasible nodes (tier-affinity constraint, Equation 6) |
| `/prioritize` | POST | Score nodes using PPO policy + LSTM-AE predictions |
| `/health` | GET | Health check for liveness/readiness probes |
| `/metrics` | GET | Prometheus metrics (scheduling latency, decision counts) |

The extender returns scored node rankings within the **100 ms** Kubernetes scheduling timeout. Measured critical-path latency: **~17.5 ms** per scheduling decision (Table 3 in the paper).

---

## Monitoring

Prometheus metrics are scraped automatically. Import the Grafana dashboard:

```bash
kubectl apply -f k8s/manifests/grafana-dashboard-configmap.yaml
```

The dashboard shows:
- Scheduling latency (p50, p95, p99)
- SHAP feature attributions (updated every 60 s)
- LSTM-AE forecasts vs. actual workload
- Anomaly alerts
- Per-node CPU utilization and energy consumption

---

## Running the RUBiS Workload

```bash
# Deploy RUBiS with 500 concurrent users
kubectl apply -f datasets/rubis/k8s/
kubectl wait --for=condition=ready pod -l app=rubis --timeout=300s

# Run 2-hour experiment
python datasets/rubis/load_generator.py \
  --target $(kubectl get svc rubis-frontend -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].ip}') \
  --users 500 \
  --duration 7200 \
  --output results/kubernetes/rubis_traces.csv

# Collect results
python experiments/evaluate.py \
  --config configs/kubernetes.yaml \
  --output results/kubernetes/evaluation.json
```

---

## Energy Measurement

Energy consumption in the Kubernetes experiments was measured using **IPMI power sensors** at 1-second granularity:

```bash
# Install ipmitool on each node
apt-get install ipmitool

# Collect power readings (run on each node)
python scripts/collect_power.py \
  --interval 1 \
  --duration 7200 \
  --output results/kubernetes/power_node_<hostname>.csv

# Aggregate
python scripts/aggregate_energy.py \
  --power_dir results/kubernetes/ \
  --output results/kubernetes/energy_summary.json
```

---

## Cleanup

```bash
kubectl delete namespace hwoa-rl-xai
kubectl delete -f k8s/manifests/scheduler-policy.yaml -n kube-system
```
